                </embeetle:fieldKindCmt>
              </vendorExtensions>
            </field>
          </fields>
        </register>
        <register>
          <name>SMPTIM1</name>
          <displayName>ADC Sampling Time Register 1</displayName>
          <description>
            Configures the sample times for ADC channels 0 to 9. Each channel is assigned
            a 3-bit field, indicating the number of ADC clock cycles used for sampling.
          </description>
          <addressOffset>0xC</addressOffset>
          <size>32</size>
          <access>read-write</access>
          <protection>n</protection>
          <resetValue>0x0</resetValue>
          <resetMask>0xFFFFFFFF</resetMask>
          <fields>
            <field>
              <name>SMPCYCCFG1</name>
              <displayName>Sample Time Configuration 1</displayName>
              <description>
                SMPCYCCFG1 covers multiple channels (channels 0..9, 3 bits each = 30 bits),
                but here it's only 27 bits in total. The chapter indicates 8 or 10 channels
                per register, etc. This is a summary of possible arrangement.
                SMPCYCCFG1 holds the sample time configurations (3 bits per channel) for
                multiple ADC channels. Each 3-bit field defines the number of cycles for
                sampling:
                000 = 3 cycles,
                001 = 15 cycles,
                010 = 28 cycles,
                011 = 56 cycles,
                100 = 84 cycles,
                101 = 112 cycles,
                110 = 144 cycles,
                111 = 480 cycles.
                Note: Only 27 bits are used here (9 channels x 3 bits).
              </description>
              <bitOffset>0</bitOffset>
              <bitWidth>27</bitWidth>
              <access>read-write</access>
              <vendorExtensions>
                <embeetle:fieldKind>setting</embeetle:fieldKind>
                <embeetle:fieldKindCmt>
                  Typically set during initialization to configure each channel's
                  sampling time for channels covered by SMPTIM1.
                </embeetle:fieldKindCmt>
              </vendorExtensions>
            </field>
          </fields>
        </register>
        <register>
          <name>SMPTIM2</name>
          <displayName>ADC Sampling Time Register 2</displayName>
          <description>
            Configures the sample times for additional ADC channels (e.g. 10 to 17). Each
            channel is assigned a 3-bit field, indicating the number of ADC clock cycles
            used for sampling.
          </description>
          <addressOffset>0x10</addressOffset>
          <size>32</size>
          <access>read-write</access>
          <protection>n</protection>
          <resetValue>0x0</resetValue>
          <resetMask>0xFFFFFFFF</resetMask>
          <fields>
            <field>
              <name>SMPCYCCFG2</name>
              <displayName>Sample Time Configuration 2</displayName>
              <description>
                SMPCYCCFG2 covers more channels with 3 bits each. According to the chapter,
                30 bits might be enough for 10 channels.
                SMPCYCCFG2 holds the sample time configurations (3 bits per channel) for
                additional ADC channels. Each 3-bit field defines the number of cycles for
                sampling:
                000 = 3 cycles,
                001 = 15 cycles,
                010 = 28 cycles,
                011 = 56 cycles,
                100 = 84 cycles,
                101 = 112 cycles,
                110 = 144 cycles,
                111 = 480 cycles.
                Note: 30 bits used here (10 channels x 3 bits).
              </description>
              <bitOffset>0</bitOffset>
              <bitWidth>30</bitWidth>
              <access>read-write</access>
              <vendorExtensions>
                <embeetle:fieldKind>setting</embeetle:fieldKind>
                <embeetle:fieldKindCmt>
                  Typically set during initialization to configure each channel's
                  sampling time for channels covered by SMPTIM2.
                </embeetle:fieldKindCmt>
              </vendorExtensions>
            </field>
          </fields>
        </register>
        <register>
          <name>STS</name>
          <displayName>ADC Status Register</displayName>
          <description>
            Reports various ADC status flags such as analog watchdog event, end of
            conversion for both regular and injected channels, start flags, and
            overrun detection.
          </description>
          <addressOffset>0x0</addressOffset>
          <size>32</size>
          <access>read-write</access>
          <protection>n</protection>
          <resetValue>0x0</resetValue>
          <resetMask>0xFFFFFFFF</resetMask>
          <fields>
            <field>
              <name>AWDFLG</name>
              <displayName>Analog Watchdog Flag</displayName>
              <description>
                Indicates whether an analog watchdog event has occurred (voltage out
                of the configured thresholds).
              </description>
              <bitOffset>0</bitOffset>
              <bitWidth>1</bitWidth>
              <access>read-write</access>
              <vendorExtensions>
                <embeetle:fieldKind>runtime</embeetle:fieldKind>
                <embeetle:fieldKindCmt>
                  Cleared by software after handling the watchdog event.
                </embeetle:fieldKindCmt>
              </vendorExtensions>
            </field>
            <field>
              <name>EOCFLG</name>
              <displayName>End of Conversion Flag (Regular)</displayName>
              <description>
                Indicates whether a regular channel conversion has completed.
              </description>
              <bitOffset>1</bitOffset>
              <bitWidth>1</bitWidth>
              <access>read-write</access>
              <vendorExtensions>
                <embeetle:fieldKind>runtime</embeetle:fieldKind>
                <embeetle:fieldKindCmt>
                  Typically cleared by reading the ADC data register or by
                  software in the ISR.
                </embeetle:fieldKindCmt>
              </vendorExtensions>
            </field>
            <field>
              <name>INJEOCFLG</name>
              <displayName>End of Conversion Flag (Injected)</displayName>
              <description>
                Indicates whether an injected channel conversion has completed.
              </description>
              <bitOffset>2</bitOffset>
              <bitWidth>1</bitWidth>
              <access>read-write</access>
              <vendorExtensions>
                <embeetle:fieldKind>runtime</embeetle:fieldKind>
                <embeetle:fieldKindCmt>
                  Typically cleared by reading the injected data registers or
                  by software in the ISR.
                </embeetle:fieldKindCmt>
              </vendorExtensions>
            </field>
            <field>
              <name>INJCSFLG</name>
              <displayName>Injected Channel Start Flag</displayName>
              <description>
                Indicates whether an injected channel conversion has started.
              </description>
              <bitOffset>3</bitOffset>
              <bitWidth>1</bitWidth>
              <access>read-write</access>
              <vendorExtensions>
                <embeetle:fieldKind>runtime</embeetle:fieldKind>
                <embeetle:fieldKindCmt>
                  Can be used to monitor if the ADC began injected channel conversion.
                  Cleared by hardware when the conversion ends or by software.
                </embeetle:fieldKindCmt>
              </vendorExtensions>
            </field>
            <field>
              <name>REGCSFLG</name>
              <displayName>Regular Channel Start Flag</displayName>
              <description>
                Indicates whether a regular channel conversion has started.
              </description>
              <bitOffset>4</bitOffset>
              <bitWidth>1</bitWidth>
              <access>read-write</access>
              <vendorExtensions>
                <embeetle:fieldKind>runtime</embeetle:fieldKind>
                <embeetle:fieldKindCmt>
                  Can be used to monitor if the ADC began regular channel conversion.
                  Cleared by hardware when the conversion ends or by software.
                </embeetle:fieldKindCmt>
              </vendorExtensions>
            </field>
            <field>
              <name>OVRFLG</name>
              <displayName>Overrun Flag</displayName>
              <description>
                Indicates an overrun event occurred (new data overwritten before
                previous data was read).
              </description>
              <bitOffset>5</bitOffset>
              <bitWidth>1</bitWidth>
              <access>read-write</access>
              <vendorExtensions>
                <embeetle:fieldKind>runtime</embeetle:fieldKind>
                <embeetle:fieldKindCmt>
                  Typically cleared by software after acknowledging the overrun.
                </embeetle:fieldKindCmt>
              </vendorExtensions>
            </field>
          </fields>
        </register>
      </registers>
    </peripheral>
    <peripheral>
      <name>CAN1</name>
      <description>Controller area network</description>
      <groupName>CAN</groupName>
      <baseAddress>0x40006400</baseAddress>
      <addressBlock>
        <offset>0x0</offset>
        <size>0x400</size>
        <usage>registers</usage>
        <protection>n</protection>
      </addressBlock>
      <interrupt>
        <name>CAN1_TX</name>
        <description>CAN1 TX interrupts</description>
        <value>19</value>
      </interrupt>
      <interrupt>
        <name>CAN1_RX0</name>
        <description>CAN1 RX0 interrupts</description>
        <value>20</value>
      </interrupt>
      <interrupt>
        <name>CAN1_RX1</name>
        <description>CAN1 RX1 interrupts</description>
        <value>21</value>
      </interrupt>
      <interrupt>
        <name>CAN1_SCE</name>
        <description>CAN1 SCE interrupt</description>
        <value>22</value>
      </interrupt>
      <registers>
        <register>
          <name>BITTIM</name>
          <displayName>CAN Bit Timing Register</displayName>
          <description>Configures the CAN bit timing parameters (such as prescaler and time segments). This register is only accessible in Initialization mode.</description>
          <addressOffset>0x1C</addressOffset>
          <size>32</size>
          <access>read-write</access>
          <protection>n</protection>
          <resetValue>0x01230000</resetValue>
          <resetMask>0xFFFFFFFF</resetMask>
          <fields>
            <field>
              <name>BRPSC</name>
              <displayName>Baud Rate Prescaler</displayName>
              <description>Sets the baud rate prescaler: Tq = (BRPSC + 1) x TPCLK</description>
              <bitOffset>0</bitOffset>
              <bitWidth>10</bitWidth>
              <access>read-write</access>
              <vendorExtensions>
                <embeetle:fieldKind>setting</embeetle:fieldKind>
                <embeetle:fieldKindCmt>This prescaler is typically configured once during CAN initialization.</embeetle:fieldKindCmt>
              </vendorExtensions>
            </field>
            <field>
              <name>TIMSEG1</name>
              <displayName>Time Segment 1</displayName>
              <description>Configures Time Segment 1 (BS1). The duration is tBS1 = tCAN x (TIMSEG1 + 1)</description>
              <bitOffset>16</bitOffset>
              <bitWidth>4</bitWidth>
              <access>read-write</access>
              <vendorExtensions>
                <embeetle:fieldKind>setting</embeetle:fieldKind>
                <embeetle:fieldKindCmt>Time segment 1 is set during CAN initialization.</embeetle:fieldKindCmt>
              </vendorExtensions>
            </field>
            <field>
              <name>TIMSEG2</name>
              <displayName>Time Segment 2</displayName>
              <description>Configures Time Segment 2 (BS2). The duration is tBS2 = tCAN x (TIMSEG2 + 1)</description>
              <bitOffset>20</bitOffset>
              <bitWidth>3</bitWidth>
              <access>read-write</access>
              <vendorExtensions>
                <embeetle:fieldKind>setting</embeetle:fieldKind>
                <embeetle:fieldKindCmt>Time segment 2 is set during CAN initialization.</embeetle:fieldKindCmt>
              </vendorExtensions>
            </field>
            <field>
              <name>RSYNJW</name>
              <displayName>Resynchronization Jump Width</displayName>
              <description>Configures the resynchronization jump width: tRJW = tCAN x (RSYNJW + 1)</description>
              <bitOffset>24</bitOffset>
              <bitWidth>2</bitWidth>
              <access>read-write</access>
              <vendorExtensions>
                <embeetle:fieldKind>setting</embeetle:fieldKind>
                <embeetle:fieldKindCmt>The resynchronization jump width is set during CAN initialization.</embeetle:fieldKindCmt>
              </vendorExtensions>
            </field>
            <field>
              <name>LBKMEN</name>
              <displayName>Loopback Mode Enable</displayName>
              <description>Enables or disables Loopback mode for CAN self‑test. Valid only while in Initialization mode.</description>
              <bitOffset>30</bitOffset>
              <bitWidth>1</bitWidth>
              <access>read-write</access>
              <enumeratedValues>
                <enumeratedValue>
                  <name>DISABLE</name>
                  <displayName>DISABLE</displayName>
                  <description>Loopback mode disabled</description>
                  <value>0</value>
                </enumeratedValue>
                <enumeratedValue>
                  <name>ENABLE</name>
                  <displayName>ENABLE</displayName>
                  <description>Loopback mode enabled</description>
                  <value>1</value>
                </enumeratedValue>
              </enumeratedValues>
              <vendorExtensions>
                <embeetle:fieldKind>setting</embeetle:fieldKind>
                <embeetle:fieldKindCmt>Loopback mode is selected only during CAN initialization.</embeetle:fieldKindCmt>
              </vendorExtensions>
            </field>
            <field>
              <name>SILMEN</name>
              <displayName>Silent Mode Enable</displayName>
              <description>Enables or disables Silent (mute) mode. Valid only while in Initialization mode.</description>
              <bitOffset>31</bitOffset>
              <bitWidth>1</bitWidth>
              <access>read-write</access>
              <enumeratedValues>
                <enumeratedValue>
                  <name>DISABLE</name>
                  <displayName>DISABLE</displayName>
                  <description>Silent mode disabled (normal operation)</description>
                  <value>0</value>
                </enumeratedValue>
                <enumeratedValue>
                  <name>ENABLE</name>
                  <displayName>ENABLE</displayName>
                  <description>Silent (mute) mode enabled</description>
                  <value>1</value>
                </enumeratedValue>
              </enumeratedValues>
              <vendorExtensions>
                <embeetle:fieldKind>setting</embeetle:fieldKind>
                <embeetle:fieldKindCmt>Silent mode is selected only during CAN initialization.</embeetle:fieldKindCmt>
              </vendorExtensions>
            </field>
          </fields>
        </register>
        <register>
          <name>ERRSTS</name>
          <displayName>CAN Error Status Register</displayName>
          <description>Reflects various CAN error states and counters, including warning, passive, and bus-off conditions.</description>
          <addressOffset>0x18</addressOffset>
          <size>32</size>
          <protection>n</protection>
          <resetValue>0x00000000</resetValue>
          <resetMask>0xFFFFFFFF</resetMask>
          <fields>
            <field>
              <name>ERRWFLG</name>
              <displayName>Error Warning Flag</displayName>
              <description>Indicates that the CAN controller has reached the error warning level (RX or TX error counter ≥ 96).</description>
              <bitOffset>0</bitOffset>
              <bitWidth>1</bitWidth>
              <access>read-only</access>
              <enumeratedValues>
                <enumeratedValue>
                  <name>NO_WARNING</name>
                  <displayName>NO_WARNING</displayName>
                  <description>No error warning occurred.</description>
                  <value>0</value>
                </enumeratedValue>
                <enumeratedValue>
                  <name>WARNING</name>
                  <displayName>WARNING</displayName>
                  <description>Error warning level reached.</description>
                  <value>1</value>
                </enumeratedValue>
              </enumeratedValues>
              <vendorExtensions>
                <embeetle:fieldKind>runtime</embeetle:fieldKind>
                <embeetle:fieldKindCmt>Software reads this flag at runtime to detect error warnings.</embeetle:fieldKindCmt>
              </vendorExtensions>
            </field>
            <field>
              <name>ERRPFLG</name>
              <displayName>Error Passive Flag</displayName>
              <description>Indicates that the CAN controller has entered error passive (RX or TX error counter &gt; 127).</description>
              <bitOffset>1</bitOffset>
              <bitWidth>1</bitWidth>
              <access>read-only</access>
              <enumeratedValues>
                <enumeratedValue>
                  <name>NO_PASSIVE</name>
                  <displayName>NO_PASSIVE</displayName>
                  <description>No passive error occurred.</description>
                  <value>0</value>
                </enumeratedValue>
                <enumeratedValue>
                  <name>PASSIVE</name>
                  <displayName>PASSIVE</displayName>
                  <description>Controller is in error passive state.</description>
                  <value>1</value>
                </enumeratedValue>
              </enumeratedValues>
              <vendorExtensions>
                <embeetle:fieldKind>runtime</embeetle:fieldKind>
                <embeetle:fieldKindCmt>Software reads this flag at runtime to detect when the controller is in error passive.</embeetle:fieldKindCmt>
              </vendorExtensions>
            </field>
            <field>
              <name>BOFLG</name>
              <displayName>Bus-Off Flag</displayName>
              <description>Indicates that the CAN controller has entered bus-off (TX error counter &gt; 255).</description>
              <bitOffset>2</bitOffset>
              <bitWidth>1</bitWidth>
              <access>read-only</access>
              <enumeratedValues>
                <enumeratedValue>
                  <name>ACTIVE</name>
                  <displayName>ACTIVE</displayName>
                  <description>CAN controller is not bus-off.</description>
                  <value>0</value>
                </enumeratedValue>
                <enumeratedValue>
                  <name>BUS_OFF</name>
                  <displayName>BUS_OFF</displayName>
                  <description>CAN controller is bus-off.</description>
                  <value>1</value>
                </enumeratedValue>
              </enumeratedValues>
              <vendorExtensions>
                <embeetle:fieldKind>runtime</embeetle:fieldKind>
                <embeetle:fieldKindCmt>Software reads this flag at runtime to detect bus-off state.</embeetle:fieldKindCmt>
              </vendorExtensions>
            </field>
            <field>
              <name>LERRC</name>
              <displayName>Last Error Code</displayName>
              <description>Records the category of the last detected CAN error. Cleared to 0 on successful transmission/reception.</description>
              <bitOffset>4</bitOffset>
              <bitWidth>3</bitWidth>
              <access>read-write</access>
              <enumeratedValues>
                <enumeratedValue>
                  <name>NO_ERROR</name>
                  <displayName>NO_ERROR</displayName>
                  <description>No error.</description>
                  <value>0</value>
                </enumeratedValue>
                <enumeratedValue>
                  <name>BIT_STUFFING_ERROR</name>
                  <displayName>BIT_STUFFING_ERROR</displayName>
                  <description>Bit stuffing error detected.</description>
                  <value>1</value>
                </enumeratedValue>
                <enumeratedValue>
                  <name>FORM_ERROR</name>
                  <displayName>FORM_ERROR</displayName>
                  <description>Form error detected.</description>
                  <value>2</value>
                </enumeratedValue>
                <enumeratedValue>
                  <name>ACK_ERROR</name>
                  <displayName>ACK_ERROR</displayName>
                  <description>ACK error detected.</description>
                  <value>3</value>
                </enumeratedValue>
                <enumeratedValue>
                  <name>RECESSIVE_BIT_ERROR</name>
                  <displayName>RECESSIVE_BIT_ERROR</displayName>
                  <description>Recessive bit error detected.</description>
                  <value>4</value>
                </enumeratedValue>
                <enumeratedValue>
                  <name>DOMINANT_BIT_ERROR</name>
                  <displayName>DOMINANT_BIT_ERROR</displayName>
                  <description>Dominant bit error detected.</description>
                  <value>5</value>
                </enumeratedValue>
                <enumeratedValue>
                  <name>CRC_ERROR</name>
                  <displayName>CRC_ERROR</displayName>
                  <description>CRC error detected.</description>
                  <value>6</value>
                </enumeratedValue>
                <enumeratedValue>
                  <name>SOFTWARE_SET</name>
                  <displayName>SOFTWARE_SET</displayName>
                  <description>Bit manually set by software.</description>
                  <value>7</value>
                </enumeratedValue>
              </enumeratedValues>
              <vendorExtensions>
                <embeetle:fieldKind>runtime</embeetle:fieldKind>
                <embeetle:fieldKindCmt>Software may read or reset this code at runtime for debugging or error handling.</embeetle:fieldKindCmt>
              </vendorExtensions>
            </field>
            <field>
              <name>TXERRCNT</name>
              <displayName>Transmit Error Counter</displayName>
              <description>Reflects the current transmit error counter. When it exceeds 255, the controller enters bus-off.</description>
              <bitOffset>16</bitOffset>
              <bitWidth>8</bitWidth>
              <access>read-only</access>
              <vendorExtensions>
                <embeetle:fieldKind>runtime</embeetle:fieldKind>
                <embeetle:fieldKindCmt>Software reads this counter at runtime to diagnose CAN transmission reliability.</embeetle:fieldKindCmt>
              </vendorExtensions>
            </field>
            <field>
              <name>RXERRCNT</name>
              <displayName>Receive Error Counter</displayName>
              <description>Reflects the current receive error counter. When it exceeds 127, the controller enters error passive.</description>
              <bitOffset>24</bitOffset>
              <bitWidth>8</bitWidth>
              <access>read-only</access>
              <vendorExtensions>
                <embeetle:fieldKind>runtime</embeetle:fieldKind>
                <embeetle:fieldKindCmt>Software reads this counter at runtime to diagnose CAN reception reliability.</embeetle:fieldKindCmt>
              </vendorExtensions>
            </field>
          </fields>
        </register>
        <register>
          <name>F0BANK1</name>
          <displayName>Filter Bank 0 Register 1</displayName>
          <description>
            FiBANKx: Filter Bank i Register x (i=0..27, x=1..2).
            Stores the 32 filter bits for filter bank i (register x). Depending on the filter mode (mask or identifier list)
            and bit width (16-bit or 32-bit) configured via CAN_FMCFG and CAN_FSCFG, these 32 bits are interpreted either as
            mask bits or identifier bits for filtering CAN messages. In "identifier mask" mode, a bit of '1' in this register
            indicates that the corresponding ID bit must match. In "identifier list" mode, these bits form part of the exact
            ID pattern. The register can only be modified if the filter is in initialization mode (FINITEN=1 in CAN_FCTRL) or
            if the filter is disabled (FACTx=0). Once activated, the filter logic will use these bits, in conjunction with
            the other filter bank register (FiBANK1 or FiBANK2), to decide which incoming CAN messages pass to the receive FIFO.
          </description>
          <addressOffset>0x240</addressOffset>
          <size>32</size>
          <access>read-write</access>
          <protection>n</protection>
          <resetValue>0x0</resetValue>
          <resetMask>0xFFFFFFFF</resetMask>
          <fields>
            <field><name>FBIT0</name><description>Filter bits</description><bitOffset>0</bitOffset><bitWidth>1</bitWidth></field>
            <field><name>FBIT1</name><description>Filter bits</description><bitOffset>1</bitOffset><bitWidth>1</bitWidth></field>
            <field><name>FBIT2</name><description>Filter bits</description><bitOffset>2</bitOffset><bitWidth>1</bitWidth></field>
